> Argentina is renowned for incredible steaks, so it goes without saying that they
> know how to dress them up right. Chimichurri is an Argentinian herb sauce
> traditionally made with green herbs, vinegar, garlic, and plenty of olive oil.
> Here we used mellow scallion greens for our own twist. Served over cumin-scented
> steak, it's an unbeatable combination.

Wash and dry all produce. Bring a large #pot of salted water to boil. Core, seed,
and thinly slice the @red bell pepper{1}. Mince or grate @garlic{2%cloves}. Thinly
slice @scallions{2}(whites and greens separated).

Very finely mince the scallion greens. Zest, then halve the @lemon{1} (you'll
want about ½ teaspoon zest).

Heat a drizzle of @olive oil{} in a large pan over medium-high heat. Add the red
bell pepper and cook, tossing for ~{4-5%minutes}, until softened. Add the scallion
whites and garlic and cook for another ~{1%minute}, until fragrant. Season with
@salt{} and @pepper{} and set aside in a #medium bowl{}.

Season the @sirloin steak{12%oz} on all sides with @cumin{1%tsp}, salt, and
pepper. Heat another drizzle of @olive oil{} in the same #pan over high heat.
Add the steak to the pan and cook for ~{4-7%minutes} per side, or until cooked
to desired doneness. Set aside to rest for ~{5%minutes}.

Meanwhile, add the @Israeli couscous{3/4%cup} to the boiling water and cook for
~{7-9%minutes}, until al dente. Drain (just like pasta).

== Spinach Couscous Salad ==

Once ready, toss the cooked couscous into the red pepper mixture along with the
@spinach{5%oz}, lemon zest, and a drizzle of @olive oil{}. Season to taste with
@salt{} and @pepper{}.

== Scallion Chimichurri ==

In a #small bowl{}, combine the scallion greens, a large drizzle of
@olive oil{}, and a squeeze of lemon juice. Season to taste with salt and pepper.

== To Serve ==

Thinly slice the Argentinian-spiced steak against the grain and serve on a bed of
spinach couscous salad. Top with the scallion chimichurri and enjoy!